---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { KIT_SLUG, KIT_PDF_PATH, KIT_BUILDER_PATH, KIT_LOADER_PATH, KIT_LOADING_GUIDE_PATH, KIT_CHEATSHEET_PATH, KIT_FAMILY_VAULT_BUILDER_PATH, KIT_FIELD_GUIDE_PATH } from '../../../consts';

// One static page at the fixed slug. Hidden, noindex, unlinked (spec §4).
export function getStaticPaths() {
  return [{ params: { slug: KIT_SLUG } }];
}
---
<BaseLayout
  title="The Load-Bearing Library"
  description="Every kit, template, and structure I've released — free to take and adapt."
  noindex={true}
>
  <div class="eyebrow"><span class="dot"></span>Load-Bearing<span class="sep">·</span>Library</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">The Library</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Everything I've released — the structures, templates, and kits underneath the systems I write
    about. Free to take and adapt. <b>New ones land here</b> as they ship.
  </p>

  <section class="lib">
    <article class="res">
      <div class="res-meta">PDF guide + Markdown builder</div>
      <h2>The Context Vault</h2>
      <p>
        Give your AI a memory that's actually yours — a folder of plain files you own, not a product
        you rent. The three-layer folder structure, the anchor template, the <span class="mono">AGENTS.md</span>
        entry file every agent reads first, and the prompts that load context.
      </p>
      <p class="sub">
        New: the <b>builder</b> — a Markdown file you hand to your AI. It interviews you and builds the
        vault with you, filled in for your actual projects. Download it, upload it to your assistant,
        and say “run this.”
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn" href={KIT_PDF_PATH}>Download the guide (PDF) &rarr;</a>
        <a class="btn alt" href={KIT_BUILDER_PATH}>Get the builder &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="res">
      <div class="res-meta">Markdown loader</div>
      <h2>The Context Vault — Loader</h2>
      <p>
        Once the vault exists, this fills it — with the knowledge you already have, scattered across
        old AI chats, folders, and repos. You hand the Loader to your AI; it extracts each source into
        a staging file you review, then compiles the approved parts into durable pages. Two steps,
        never one, so a stray hallucination never reaches your permanent memory.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn alt" href={KIT_LOADER_PATH}>Get the Loader &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="res">
      <div class="res-meta">PDF guide</div>
      <h2>Loading Guide</h2>
      <p>
        The human-readable half of the Loader: the extract-then-compile method in plain English — why
        you stage before you commit, why the AI proposes decisions instead of minting them, and the
        keep-it-fed loops that stop slow rot. Read it to understand what the Loader is doing.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn" href={KIT_LOADING_GUIDE_PATH}>Download the guide (PDF) &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="res">
      <div class="res-meta">Markdown cheat-sheet</div>
      <h2>Use It Anywhere — Cheat-Sheet</h2>
      <p>
        One page for <b>using</b> the vault you built: the three ways to load the right slice into any
        AI tool — paste it, attach it to a project, or point an agent at the folder — plus a
        per-assistant table (ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, editors, local models) and what to trim before
        you send.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn alt" href={KIT_CHEATSHEET_PATH}>Get the cheat-sheet &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </article>

          <article class="res">
            <div class="res-meta">Markdown builder</div>
            <h2>Personal &amp; Family — Family Vault Builder</h2>
            <p>
              The same idea, pointed at your life instead of your work: a builder you hand to your AI and
              it interviews you — food, travel, the kids, the household — then sets up a <b>family vault</b>
              with the keep-it-separate boundary baked in, so the assistants you use for work can't read it.
            </p>
            <div class="btn-row">
              <a class="btn alt" href={KIT_FAMILY_VAULT_BUILDER_PATH}>Get the builder &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </article>

        <article class="res">
          <div class="res-meta">PDF field guide</div>
          <h2>Assemble, Don't Build</h2>
          <p>
            The build-vs-buy question, retired: it was never build-vs-buy, it's <b>which layer</b>. A
            decision framework for composing your own agent stack — the two-question test to run on
            every component, the six-layer map (four you rent, two you own), the four-question gate
            test, and the one invariant that survives full autonomy: <span class="mono">fail loud</span>.
            Ends with a worksheet to map your own stack.
          </p>
          <div class="btn-row">
            <a class="btn" href={KIT_FIELD_GUIDE_PATH}>Download the field guide (PDF) &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </article>
  </section>

  <p class="lib-foot">
    <b>Load-Bearing</b> is a newsletter about building real AI systems from first principles. If a
    friend sent you here, the kit + newsletter are free — <a href="/subscribe">grab them</a> and you'll
    get a heads-up whenever something new lands in the library.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .lib { display: grid; gap: 18px; }
  .res {
    position: relative; background: var(--bg-panel); border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 14px; padding: 24px 24px 22px 28px; transition: border-color .15s;
  }
  .res:hover { border-color: var(--signal); }
  .res::before {
    content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0; top: 18px; bottom: 18px; width: 3px;
    border-radius: 3px; background: linear-gradient(180deg, var(--signal), var(--signal-deep));
  }
  .res-meta {
    font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 11.5px; letter-spacing: .18em; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-faint); margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .res h2 {
    font-family: var(--display); font-weight: 600; font-size: clamp(20px,3vw,25px);
    margin: 0 0 8px; letter-spacing: -.02em; color: var(--heading);
  }
  .res p { color: var(--text-soft); font-size: 15.5px; margin: 0 0 16px; max-width: 56ch; }
  .res p .mono { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: .9em; }
  .res .sub { color: var(--text-faint); font-size: 14px; margin: -4px 0 16px; }
  .res .sub b { color: var(--text-soft); font-weight: 600; }
  .lib-foot {
    margin-top: 40px; padding-top: 24px; border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    font-size: 14px; color: var(--text-faint); max-width: 60ch;
  }
  .lib-foot b { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
</style>
